<title>About sorcerers: their death, their snoring work, earthquakes and the rain</title>
<summary><i>Further details concerning what occurs at the death of a sorcerer, and concerning the harmful and beneficial doings of sorcerers (L V.-19. 5506-5530). When a sorcerer dies, an earthquake takes place, and a star shoots. Even when asleep, a sorcerer knows what is going about in the night; and takes care of the people, defending them from the sorcerers. (L V.-19. 5531-5536 1/2).</i> Sorcerers&apos; hearts sound like the rain when they die and their hearts fall into waterpits. Parents say they fear falling stars, because they know things that happen and always fall for a reason. Sorcerers can send their sorcery to different places to &apos;spirit&apos; people away or kill them.</summary><comments>1) Dia!kwain was told this story by his mother (≠kamme-an), 2) pp.5505v &amp; 5506v: see <i>Dia!kwain&apos;s explanation of the name which his mother gave him</i>, 3) pp.5506v-5512v: see <i>More about sorcerers</i>, 4) p.5524v: |xam terms for the anointing and smearing of blood from the healer&apos;s nose on the patient, 5) See also <i>Falling stars</i>, 6) This story is found in Book V-19</comments><date>11 November 1875 (started)</date><storypages>5506-5536 1/2</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><category>Healing and ailing</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>sorcerers</kw><subkw>about sorcerers and their work</subkw></keyword>
